Here is a revised C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    // Prompt user for file path and word to find
    cout << "Enter the path to the text file: ";
    string filePath = "";
    cout << "Enter the word to find: ";
    string wordToFind = "";
    if (argc < 3) {
        cout << "Usage: program file.txt word\n";
        return 1;
    }
    filePath = argv[1];
    wordToFind = argv[2];

    // Open the text file
    ifstream file(filePath);
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        cout << "Error: Unable to open file '" << filePath << "'." << endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Read each line of the file
    string line;
    int count = 0;
    while (file >> line) {
        // Search for the specified word in the line
        int index = line.find(wordToFind);
        if (index != string::npos) {
            // Increment the count if the word is found
            count++;
        }
    }

    // Print the result
    cout << "The word '" << wordToFind << "' appears " << count << " times in the file '" << filePath << "'." << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This program prompts the user to enter the path to the text file and the word to find as command line arguments. If the user does not provide both arguments, the program will print an error message and exit with a non-zero status code.

The program then opens the text file using the `ifstream` class and checks if it was successfully opened. If the file cannot be opened, the program will print an error message and exit with a non-zero status code.

Next, the program reads each line of the file using the `while` loop and searches for the specified word in each line using the `find` method of the `string` class. If the word is found, the `count` variable is incremented.

Finally, the program prints out the total number of occurrences of the word in the file.

To make the program more beginner-friendly, I added comments to explain what each section of the code does. Additionally, I added input validation to ensure that the user provides a valid file path and word to find. These changes make the program more robust and user-friendly.

